<paper id="1597414920"><title>Model Checking - Timed UML State Machines and Collaborations</title><year>2002</year><authors><author org="Ludwig-Maximilians-Universität München" id="2161420078">Alexander Knapp</author><author org="Ludwig-Maximilians-Universität München" id="2097000653">Stephan Merz</author><author org="Technische Universität München;" id="2575642316">Christopher Rauh</author></authors><n_citation>165</n_citation><doc_type>Journal</doc_type><references><reference>1497879578</reference><reference>1528367975</reference><reference>1570069626</reference><reference>1570394779</reference><reference>1582068322</reference><reference>1977237988</reference><reference>2000947342</reference><reference>2020034474</reference><reference>2024047464</reference><reference>2099529102</reference><reference>2100500368</reference><reference>2101508170</reference><reference>2116419508</reference><reference>2121163444</reference><reference>2141706812</reference><reference>2159765281</reference><reference>2897840903</reference></references><venue id="106296714" type="J">Lecture Notes in Computer Science</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-45739-9_23</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.51423">Model checking</keyword><keyword weight="0.45129">Programming language</keyword><keyword weight="0.46782">Unified Modeling Language</keyword><keyword weight="0.43753">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.43996">Critical section</keyword><keyword weight="0.50646">Automaton</keyword><keyword weight="0.5532">Finite-state machine</keyword><keyword weight="0.42824">Real-time computing</keyword><keyword weight="0.76435">Timed automaton</keyword><keyword weight="0.53539">Network automaton</keyword><keyword weight="0.45428">Observer (quantum physics)</keyword><keyword weight="0.43262">Distributed computing</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>We describe a prototype tool, HUGO/RT, that is designed to automatically verify whether the timed state machines in a UML model interact according to scenarios specified by time-annotated UML collaborations. Timed state machines are compiled into timed automata that exchange signals and operations via a network automaton. A collaboration with time constraints is translated into an observer timed automaton. The model checker UPPAAL is called upon to verify the timed automata representing the model against the observer timed automaton.</abstract></paper>